# Scalability Rules (Million-Note Scale)

## Pagination

- All list queries MUST use cursor-based (keyset) pagination. Never use OFFSET.
- Return `Page<T>` with `{ items, cursor, totalEstimate }`.
- Cursor values are opaque `(sort_column, id)` tuples, base64-encoded.
- Use `sqlite_stat1` estimates or `count_cache` table for counts. Never `COUNT(*)` on large tables.

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: Keyset pagination
WHERE updated_at < ?cursor AND id < ?cursor_id
ORDER BY updated_at DESC, id DESC LIMIT 50

-- ❌ BAD: OFFSET pagination
ORDER BY updated_at DESC LIMIT 50 OFFSET 50000
```

## Queries

- Every query MUST be covered by an index. Run `EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN` to verify — no full table scans.
- Use partial indexes with `WHERE` clauses for filtered queries (e.g., `WHERE archived_at IS NULL`).
- Batch writes in transactions (max 500 rows per transaction).

## Lists & UI

- All list components MUST use virtualization (`react-window` or `FlashList`).
- Never load all items into memory. Fetch page-by-page as user scrolls.
- Show skeleton loading placeholders while fetching.
- Debounce search inputs (300ms minimum).

## Vectors

- Vector tables live in a separate `vectors.db` file (ATTACH DATABASE).
- Use IVF indexing when chunk count exceeds 100K.
- Embedding pipeline uses a persistent queue (`embedding_queue` table) with batch processing (32 per call).

## Background Processing

- All AI pipelines (NER, embedding, action extraction) are async and queue-based.
- Queues are bounded (max 1000 items). Excess items re-queued on next save.
- Queue state persists in SQLite — survives crash and restart.
